In section [8.a, The all alternates (‘aalt’) feature](http://www.adobe.com/devnet/opentype/afdko/topic_feature_file_syntax.html#8.a), the OpenType Feature File specification currently gives an example that is syntactically not well-formed. When passing the spec snippet to `makeotf`, the tool (correctly) rejects the code.

Current example feature file:
```
  feature aalt {...} aalt;
  feature scmp {...} scmp;
  feature salt {
     sub a from [a.alt1 a.alt2 a.alt2];
     sub e [c d e] f by [c.mid d.mid e.mid];
     sub b by b.alt;
  } salt;
```

Instead, the middle line of `feature salt` should have an apostrophe:
```
  feature aalt {...} aalt;
  feature scmp {...} scmp;
  feature salt {
     sub a from [a.alt1 a.alt2 a.alt2];
     sub e [c d e]' f by [c.mid d.mid e.mid];
     sub b by b.alt;
  } salt;
```

SCSS and `@extend` are wildly troublesome when used with classnames because they extend any instances where the target is the last piece of a selector. Now that you're using the following on line 109 of `_navs.scss`:

    &.nav-justified {
      @extend .nav-justified;
      @extend .nav-tabs-justified;
    }

And we use the following in our own scss:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified) { ... }`

The compiled output is:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified):not(.nav-tabs.nav-justified) { ... }`

Which is invalid CSS and breaks our styling.

When commenting out line 109 in your file, it becomes:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified)`

If you're intending to *share* styles within your own scss, I would highly advise using a placeholder so you don't copy unwanted styles, especially since this project is intended to allow for custom compilation by users.

